1
00:00:29,962 --> 00:00:32,328
WOMAN: " When he gave us
our air rifles,

2
00:00:32,364 --> 00:00:34,594
Atticus wouldn't teach us
to shoot.

3
00:00:34,633 --> 00:00:38,007
Uncle Jack instructed us in
the rudiments thereof.

4
00:00:38,023 --> 00:00:40,597
He said Atticus wasn't
interested in guns.

5
00:00:40,639 --> 00:00:42,630
And Atticus said to Jem,

6
00:00:42,674 --> 00:00:46,201
'I'd rather you shot at tin cans
in the backyard,

7
00:00:46,245 --> 00:00:48,145
but I know you'll go
after the birds.

8
00:00:48,180 --> 00:00:51,240
Shoot all the blue jays you want
if you can hit 'em,

9
00:00:51,283 --> 00:00:53,774
but remember it's a sin

10
00:00:53,819 --> 00:00:57,812
to kill a mockingbird."'
(laughs)

11
00:01:16,508 --> 00:01:19,636
Cody, take them feed sacks
to the barn.

12
00:01:19,678 --> 00:01:22,670
I think you want a ranch hand,
not a son-in-law.

13
00:01:22,714 --> 00:01:26,081
You know, with you
I'd settle for either.

14
00:01:27,553 --> 00:01:30,283
Where is my granddaughter?

15
00:01:30,322 --> 00:01:32,222
Where is she?
Come here, you.

16
00:01:32,257 --> 00:01:33,747
Come here, you.

17
00:01:33,792 --> 00:01:36,022
- (girl grunts)
- Yeah, there we go.

18
00:01:36,061 --> 00:01:40,020
WOMAN: Easy, Dad.
She's not one of your roustabouts.

19
00:01:40,065 --> 00:01:42,795
Well, she's a Banyon,
isn't she?

20
00:01:42,835 --> 00:01:44,803
At least partways.

21
00:01:44,837 --> 00:01:46,464
Best part, right, Grandpa?

22
00:01:46,505 --> 00:01:48,405
You're not just whistling Dixie.

23
00:01:48,440 --> 00:01:50,738
It's in your blood, little one.

24
00:01:50,776 --> 00:01:54,735
And now listen, since you've
proven so astoundingly proficient

25
00:01:54,780 --> 00:01:56,748
at naming horses,

26
00:01:56,782 --> 00:01:59,979
like that little spindly-legged
rockhead of a colt out there...

27
00:02:00,018 --> 00:02:03,510
- GIRL: Apache Wind.
- GRANDFATHER: Apache Wind.

28
00:02:03,555 --> 00:02:06,023
Since you did that so much better
than I expected,

29
00:02:06,058 --> 00:02:08,026
I find myself humbly in need

30
00:02:08,060 --> 00:02:11,086
of your nomenclative
services once again.

31
00:02:13,699 --> 00:02:16,167
(panting)

32
00:02:16,201 --> 00:02:19,034
Whoa!
Not just so quick.

33
00:02:19,071 --> 00:02:22,199
There is a protocol
to be observed.

34
00:02:22,241 --> 00:02:26,143
You know the naming of a horse
or a son or daughter

35
00:02:26,178 --> 00:02:28,169
or a granddaughter,
you know,

36
00:02:28,213 --> 00:02:30,545
it's not just a name.

37
00:02:30,582 --> 00:02:33,016
I mean, a name's got
to mean something to you.

38
00:02:33,051 --> 00:02:36,851
It's got to say,
"This is who I am in the world.

39
00:02:36,889 --> 00:02:39,858
I am a force
to be reckoned with."

40
00:02:41,260 --> 00:02:43,251
Okay.

41
00:02:46,165 --> 00:02:48,531
Mom, a puppy!

42
00:02:48,567 --> 00:02:51,934
A puppy?
That's not a puppy!

43
00:02:51,970 --> 00:02:55,929
Belle, that is 25 generations
of the best breeding and bloodlines

44
00:02:55,974 --> 00:02:59,137
and bearing that's ever
gone into four legs.

45
00:02:59,178 --> 00:03:01,373
- That there is...
- Atticus.

46
00:03:01,413 --> 00:03:03,313
- Who?
- Atticus.

47
00:03:03,348 --> 00:03:05,748
Oh, Mom,
can we keep him, please?

48
00:03:07,252 --> 00:03:08,879
Just a second, Belle.

49
00:03:08,921 --> 00:03:12,755
I mean, I paid a lot of money
for this dog.

50
00:03:12,791 --> 00:03:14,782
And he's gotta make me
some puppies

51
00:03:14,826 --> 00:03:17,852
so that I can make
my money back.

52
00:03:17,896 --> 00:03:19,955
Now what we could do

53
00:03:19,998 --> 00:03:22,432
is you could visit him
anytime you want

54
00:03:22,467 --> 00:03:25,868
and when the time's
a little righter,

55
00:03:25,904 --> 00:03:28,338
you could have the pick
of the litter.

56
00:03:28,373 --> 00:03:30,102
- Is that a deal?
- Deal.

57
00:03:30,142 --> 00:03:31,734
Okay.

58
00:03:31,777 --> 00:03:35,110
Well, somebody's gotta do
some work around here.

59
00:03:36,481 --> 00:03:38,472
- Bye, Dad.
- Mm-hmm.

60
00:03:52,197 --> 00:03:54,392
"I asked Miss Maudie about it.

61
00:03:54,433 --> 00:03:56,264
'Your father's right,' she said.

62
00:03:56,301 --> 00:03:58,462
'Mockingbirds don't do one thing

63
00:03:58,503 --> 00:04:00,528
but make music
for us to enjoy.

64
00:04:00,572 --> 00:04:03,598
They don't eat up
people's gardens,

65
00:04:03,642 --> 00:04:06,167
don't nest in corn cribs.

66
00:04:06,211 --> 00:04:09,203
They don't do one thing,
but sing their hearts out for us.

67
00:04:09,248 --> 00:04:11,739
That's why it's a sin

68
00:04:11,783 --> 00:04:14,149
to kill a mockingbird."'

69
00:04:18,357 --> 00:04:21,190
(thunder crashing)

70
00:04:25,931 --> 00:04:28,297
I love you, Cody.

71
00:04:29,868 --> 00:04:31,529
Belle.

72
00:04:37,276 --> 00:04:40,006
I love you, baby.
Cover up, honey.

73
00:04:45,851 --> 00:04:48,513
- Oh, my God! (screams)
- (brakes screech)

74
00:04:48,553 --> 00:04:51,420
(crashes)

75
00:05:55,120 --> 00:05:57,247
- Daddy...
- Shh!

76
00:06:22,914 --> 00:06:25,246
REVEREND: " And God shall
wipe away all tears

77
00:06:25,283 --> 00:06:27,080
from their eyes,

78
00:06:27,119 --> 00:06:29,917
and there shall be
death no more.

79
00:06:29,955 --> 00:06:33,186
Neither sorrow nor crying,

80
00:06:33,225 --> 00:06:36,922
neither shall there be
anymore pain.

81
00:06:36,962 --> 00:06:40,329
For the former things
have passed away."

82
00:08:59,604 --> 00:09:01,162
MAN:
Here you go.

83
00:09:07,479 --> 00:09:11,279
Four, eight, a tenth.

84
00:09:11,316 --> 00:09:13,546
Shoot, the man don't even
have a stopwatch.

85
00:09:13,585 --> 00:09:16,986
He's got a stopwatch.
It's in his head.

86
00:09:19,157 --> 00:09:21,648
You ought to taste
his three-minute eggs.

87
00:09:23,194 --> 00:09:26,686
You did good today,
Apache Wind, real good.

88
00:09:30,902 --> 00:09:32,927
That's a beautiful horse, Hock.

89
00:09:32,971 --> 00:09:35,769
And our consortium
is agreeable to your stud fees,

90
00:09:35,807 --> 00:09:37,638
but we are a tad concerned

91
00:09:37,676 --> 00:09:41,168
about your proposed
ownership percentages of the colt.

92
00:09:41,212 --> 00:09:44,306
Frankly, we'd just as soon own
the two-year old outright.

93
00:09:44,349 --> 00:09:46,943
That... that ain't chicken feed.

94
00:09:54,259 --> 00:09:56,693
You know,
I can't read this right now.

95
00:09:56,728 --> 00:09:58,719
I don't have my specs.

96
00:10:07,839 --> 00:10:10,865
Oh, Mrs. Wimmer,
I am so sorry.

97
00:10:10,909 --> 00:10:14,106
Oh, faddle, Lillian. Mr. Magoo
and I have nothing but time.

98
00:10:14,145 --> 00:10:16,511
Isn't that right, Magoo?

99
00:10:16,548 --> 00:10:18,641
Come on inside. Come on.

100
00:10:20,018 --> 00:10:23,044
Mrs. Wimmer, Magoo isn't due
for his parvo booster

101
00:10:23,088 --> 00:10:26,524
for another three months yet,
and even though I love seeing you,

102
00:10:26,558 --> 00:10:30,426
as I told you yesterday,
he's the perfect picture of health.

103
00:10:30,462 --> 00:10:32,987
(sighs)

104
00:10:33,031 --> 00:10:35,556
Okay, just a quick look.

105
00:10:35,600 --> 00:10:37,591
Come here, buddy.
How about some kisses?

106
00:10:37,636 --> 00:10:39,126
You wanna give me
some kisses?

107
00:10:39,170 --> 00:10:41,161
Oh, you're so cute.
You're so cute.

108
00:10:41,206 --> 00:10:44,175
Oh, Magoo!

109
00:10:44,209 --> 00:10:46,234
You did it again.

110
00:10:47,545 --> 00:10:49,274
It's okay.

111
00:10:57,922 --> 00:11:00,948
I have never seen
such concentration.

112
00:11:00,992 --> 00:11:03,620
GYM TEACHER: I wish she'd apply it
to her book work.

113
00:11:06,931 --> 00:11:08,762
Hey, Belle,

114
00:11:08,800 --> 00:11:11,394
you know who was asking
for you today?

115
00:11:11,436 --> 00:11:13,427
Who?

116
00:11:13,471 --> 00:11:15,462
Nobody!

117
00:11:35,026 --> 00:11:37,995
You guys called me out here
for another crazy cat lady?

118
00:11:38,029 --> 00:11:39,656
We'll just have to...

119
00:11:39,698 --> 00:11:41,165
Why should we have
all the fun?

120
00:11:41,199 --> 00:11:44,066
- 17 so far.
- There's one more through to the back.

121
00:11:44,102 --> 00:11:46,627
Guys, I don't have time for this.
I've got my daughter's thing...

122
00:11:46,671 --> 00:11:48,605
(cats meowing)

123
00:11:57,949 --> 00:12:00,509
- This cat got a name?
- She calls him Mrs. Snuffles.

124
00:12:00,552 --> 00:12:02,543
It's through there.

125
00:12:04,289 --> 00:12:06,484
Mrs. Snuffles!

126
00:12:06,524 --> 00:12:08,424
Kitty-kitty-kitty-kitty-kitty.

127
00:12:09,728 --> 00:12:11,923
(growls, snarls)

128
00:12:11,963 --> 00:12:13,954
(laughing)

129
00:12:15,500 --> 00:12:17,434
We got you.

130
00:12:49,400 --> 00:12:52,699
Why don't we go
to my office?

131
00:12:52,737 --> 00:12:54,728
What about my dad?

132
00:12:54,773 --> 00:12:57,241
We can talk to him together.

133
00:13:22,801 --> 00:13:26,202
- Went by the school.
- Good for you.

134
00:13:26,237 --> 00:13:28,432
You're supposed to wait for me.
That's the rule.

135
00:13:28,473 --> 00:13:30,668
Rules change.

136
00:13:30,708 --> 00:13:33,506
Mrs. Melton's pretty miffed
at you for skipping out on her.

137
00:13:33,545 --> 00:13:36,105
She'll get over it.

138
00:13:38,049 --> 00:13:40,347
Why don't you hop in?
I got another stop to make.

139
00:13:40,385 --> 00:13:43,377
I want you to see what I got
in the back. It's pretty cool stuff.

140
00:13:43,421 --> 00:13:46,356
I'd rather eat slugs.

141
00:13:46,391 --> 00:13:49,758
I was thinking pizza,
but all right.

142
00:13:51,462 --> 00:13:53,396
Belle, I'm sorry.

143
00:13:53,431 --> 00:13:56,195
You're always sorry.
You invented sorry.

144
00:14:06,177 --> 00:14:08,543
Well, you can't just let
her eat anything.

145
00:14:08,580 --> 00:14:10,844
That's why they call it
cat food, Mr. Wong.

146
00:14:10,882 --> 00:14:12,941
It's food for cats.

147
00:14:12,984 --> 00:14:15,509
I've prescribed a low ash,
high-protein diet

148
00:14:15,553 --> 00:14:18,283
and you keep giving Georgette
free range over the buffet table.

149
00:14:18,323 --> 00:14:20,655
No no, no MSG.

150
00:14:20,692 --> 00:14:23,217
That's good,
but no MSG hardly matters

151
00:14:23,261 --> 00:14:26,492
when she's gorging herself
on dim sum and moo shu pork.

152
00:14:26,531 --> 00:14:28,795
BIRD:
Here, kitty-kitty. Meow.

153
00:14:28,833 --> 00:14:32,098
Did we ask
for your opinion?

154
00:14:36,207 --> 00:14:38,198
Whew, what a day.

155
00:14:38,243 --> 00:14:40,177
No kidding, right?

156
00:14:42,513 --> 00:14:45,175
Are you sure
you won't change your mind?

157
00:14:45,216 --> 00:14:48,845
All work and no play
makes Lillian one dull, single,

158
00:14:48,887 --> 00:14:51,412
urban professional female.

159
00:14:51,456 --> 00:14:54,289
It's Friday.
We'll hit Martini Corner,

160
00:14:54,325 --> 00:14:57,089
a little dinner and a little music,

161
00:14:57,128 --> 00:14:59,289
a little dancing.

162
00:14:59,330 --> 00:15:03,061
Sounds great,
but I think I'll pass.

163
00:15:03,101 --> 00:15:05,262
Oh, shoot.

164
00:15:07,272 --> 00:15:10,332
The folks from
the Free Rural Clinic called.

165
00:15:10,375 --> 00:15:13,936
They lost their venue.
It's been called off.

166
00:15:13,978 --> 00:15:17,004
I'm sorry, Lil. I know how you like
to get out there

167
00:15:17,048 --> 00:15:19,482
with the livestock,
you know, up to your knees

168
00:15:19,517 --> 00:15:22,384
in the muck
and the cow patties.

169
00:15:23,588 --> 00:15:26,557
- I'll see you later.
- Yeah, thanks for a good day.

170
00:15:26,591 --> 00:15:27,922
You too.

171
00:15:27,959 --> 00:15:29,984
- Bye-bye, Vinny.
- Bye-bye.

172
00:15:30,028 --> 00:15:31,461
(sighs)

173
00:15:40,905 --> 00:15:42,736
Come on,
have some juice.

174
00:15:42,774 --> 00:15:45,004
- Hello.
- Hey.

175
00:15:45,043 --> 00:15:47,637
Well, hello, Vincent,
how's my bird?

176
00:15:47,679 --> 00:15:50,876
- Hello.
- Bye-bye.

177
00:15:50,915 --> 00:15:53,440
Contrary bird.

178
00:15:53,484 --> 00:15:56,044
- What's in the box?
- Pigeon.

179
00:15:56,087 --> 00:15:58,920
Oh! There are
eight million pigeons

180
00:15:58,957 --> 00:16:01,482
- in the naked city.
- And this is one of them.

181
00:16:01,526 --> 00:16:04,654
- The others didn't make it.
- When worlds collide?

182
00:16:04,696 --> 00:16:05,822
Yeah, head on.

183
00:16:05,863 --> 00:16:08,525
So this one here seems
to have already fledged.

184
00:16:08,566 --> 00:16:11,057
So I was wanting to know

185
00:16:11,102 --> 00:16:13,764
if you would keep it
quarantined here

186
00:16:13,805 --> 00:16:17,571
until I can take it out to
Wildlife Care, you know, just in case.

187
00:16:17,608 --> 00:16:20,304
Little blood work
might be prudent.

188
00:16:20,345 --> 00:16:22,779
(both gasp)

189
00:16:22,814 --> 00:16:24,941
So what do you think?

190
00:16:24,983 --> 00:16:26,951
Cody, it's not a baby pigeon.

191
00:16:26,985 --> 00:16:30,216
It's a full-grown diamond dove.
It's Australian.

192
00:16:30,254 --> 00:16:32,415
Well, that is a long way

193
00:16:32,457 --> 00:16:34,789
to come to get gassed,
little fella.

194
00:16:34,826 --> 00:16:37,192
See the ring
around his eye?

195
00:16:37,228 --> 00:16:39,355
Yeah. Wow.

196
00:16:39,397 --> 00:16:42,127
Yeah, wow is good.

197
00:16:47,205 --> 00:16:51,039
Well, I would do it myself,

198
00:16:51,075 --> 00:16:53,407
- but I've got...
- Your Belle.

199
00:16:53,444 --> 00:16:54,968
My Belle.

200
00:16:55,013 --> 00:16:56,640
I'd like to "wring" her.

201
00:16:56,681 --> 00:16:59,878
How are things?

202
00:16:59,917 --> 00:17:02,408
Oh, well, I'm pretty sure
I've slipped further down

203
00:17:02,453 --> 00:17:04,751
that formidable scale
of expectation,

204
00:17:04,789 --> 00:17:07,280
if that's at all possible.

205
00:17:07,325 --> 00:17:10,351
How long's it been now,
two years?

206
00:17:10,395 --> 00:17:13,455
Yeah, almost to the day.

207
00:17:13,498 --> 00:17:16,023
A girl her age

208
00:17:16,067 --> 00:17:19,366
should only have
happy anniversaries.

209
00:17:19,404 --> 00:17:21,133
And you?

210
00:17:21,172 --> 00:17:23,231
I don't have time
for those kind of things.

211
00:17:23,274 --> 00:17:25,265
I have a child to mis-raise.

212
00:17:27,445 --> 00:17:29,413
So you have any plans tonight?

213
00:17:29,447 --> 00:17:31,176
What did you have in mind?

214
00:17:31,215 --> 00:17:34,582
Don't panic.

215
00:17:34,619 --> 00:17:36,348
My plans include a book
and a bath,

216
00:17:36,387 --> 00:17:39,447
and if I'm really adventurous,
maybe I'll have both at the same time.

217
00:17:41,125 --> 00:17:43,025
Yeah, well,
good luck with that.

218
00:17:43,061 --> 00:17:45,154
I'm out.

219
00:17:45,196 --> 00:17:48,131
- I'll talk to you later.
- Okay.

220
00:17:50,401 --> 00:17:52,892
- Bye-bye, Vincent.
- Hello.

221
00:17:55,373 --> 00:17:57,364
(sighs)

222
00:18:04,882 --> 00:18:08,841
You know, whenever I get
the whole Belle thing leveled out,

223
00:18:08,886 --> 00:18:11,320
- some night you and I should...
- (beeper chiming)

224
00:18:11,355 --> 00:18:12,822
I'm sorry.

225
00:18:15,259 --> 00:18:16,726
Hmm.

226
00:18:16,761 --> 00:18:18,319
You were saying?

227
00:18:18,362 --> 00:18:20,922
I was saying that one
of these nights

228
00:18:20,965 --> 00:18:23,832
- that you and I should...
- (cell phone rings)

229
00:18:23,868 --> 00:18:25,631
Maybe we should?

230
00:18:25,670 --> 00:18:28,468
Hello.

231
00:18:28,506 --> 00:18:30,667
What?

232
00:18:30,708 --> 00:18:32,801
They what?

233
00:18:32,844 --> 00:18:34,835
I gotta take this.

234
00:18:38,082 --> 00:18:40,073
Uh-huh.

235
00:18:41,552 --> 00:18:43,543
Who was that?

236
00:18:45,723 --> 00:18:47,782
Don't even ask,
feather britches.

237
00:19:00,404 --> 00:19:02,895
Did you

238
00:19:02,940 --> 00:19:05,204
scrub down Apache Wind?

239
00:19:05,243 --> 00:19:07,177
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

240
00:19:09,614 --> 00:19:12,913
You want some?

241
00:19:12,950 --> 00:19:14,941
Dogs to be fed.

242
00:19:18,322 --> 00:19:20,290
(chuckles)

243
00:19:20,324 --> 00:19:23,521
You know,

244
00:19:23,561 --> 00:19:25,927
there's not a living, breathing,

245
00:19:25,963 --> 00:19:27,692
feed-swilling critter

246
00:19:27,732 --> 00:19:31,293
on these 5,000
God-splashed acres

247
00:19:31,335 --> 00:19:34,202
holds a candle
to Apache Wind.

248
00:19:35,907 --> 00:19:39,240
And my daughter picked him out

249
00:19:39,277 --> 00:19:42,144
when he was a colt,

250
00:19:42,180 --> 00:19:46,014
because that girl
knew her horseflesh.

251
00:19:48,619 --> 00:19:50,917
Ain't nothing black
as a Kansas night.

252
00:19:52,623 --> 00:19:56,252
Black as a bull's heart.

253
00:19:56,294 --> 00:19:59,991
A man ought not
to stand around ruminating

254
00:20:00,031 --> 00:20:02,261
in such darkness.

255
00:20:20,885 --> 00:20:22,853
(cats meowing)

256
00:20:22,887 --> 00:20:25,355
- Who's on duty?
- Who do you think?

257
00:20:27,625 --> 00:20:29,616
Milo.

258
00:20:30,628 --> 00:20:32,858
(barking)

259
00:20:51,382 --> 00:20:53,213
Hey, what the...

260
00:20:53,251 --> 00:20:55,685
Hey, Cody.

261
00:20:55,720 --> 00:20:58,314
- What's up, bro?
- What's up,

262
00:20:58,356 --> 00:21:01,917
Milo, is that we have collected
17 cats in your sector

263
00:21:01,959 --> 00:21:03,790
and you've refused delivery.

264
00:21:03,828 --> 00:21:06,820
What's up, bro,
is my blood pressure.

265
00:21:06,864 --> 00:21:08,798
It can't be helped.
You know what I'm saying?

266
00:21:08,833 --> 00:21:11,358
I've got two guys pulling down
time and a half because of you.

267
00:21:11,402 --> 00:21:13,199
You know my department
can't afford it.

268
00:21:13,237 --> 00:21:15,364
Get out there and help them
with the cats, man, come on.

269
00:21:15,406 --> 00:21:17,374
I don't have the room.
Know what I'm saying?

270
00:21:17,408 --> 00:21:19,569
Make the room, Milo.

271
00:21:19,610 --> 00:21:22,579
I've been making
the room for four months.

272
00:21:22,613 --> 00:21:24,478
Ever since they
shut down Number 2,

273
00:21:24,515 --> 00:21:27,143
my place has become
the dumping ground

274
00:21:27,184 --> 00:21:29,118
for half the city.

275
00:21:29,153 --> 00:21:30,882
If you want to talk budget,

276
00:21:30,921 --> 00:21:32,821
I can barely feed
what I've got.

277
00:21:32,857 --> 00:21:35,724
I don't have the room.
You know what I'm saying?

278
00:21:35,760 --> 00:21:37,728
Do your job.

279
00:21:37,762 --> 00:21:41,095
Do my job, okay.

280
00:21:41,132 --> 00:21:42,599
Okay.

281
00:21:42,633 --> 00:21:45,625
Oh, you know what?

282
00:21:45,670 --> 00:21:48,764
This is not gonna be enough, but I think
I have some more in the back.

283
00:21:48,806 --> 00:21:50,398
What are you doing?

284
00:21:50,441 --> 00:21:52,636
Just what you asked me to do.
Know what I'm saying?

285
00:21:52,677 --> 00:21:55,840
No, I don't know
what you're saying, Milo,

286
00:21:55,880 --> 00:21:58,246
because you don't know
what you're saying.

287
00:21:58,282 --> 00:22:00,750
